Notes:

Date: 2/12/1933
Source: Press, The
Author:
Vol / Page: 15
Edition:
Quote: The old names for that part of the Southern Alps and foothills which is visible from the plains. `The long range of mountains which the inhabitants of Christchurch suppose to be the backbone of the island, and which they call the Snowy Range. The real axis of the island, however, lies much farther back.' (Butler A First Year in Canterbury Settlement], p. 83). The original applications for the runs on the upper plains, in describing the locality, all end with the words `and back to the Snowy Hills' (C.)
Notes: Acland Glossary

